00:08:28.051 --> 00:08:30.693
They didn't have autism and
they were just really young

00:08:30.693 --> 00:08:34.913
but in general the interventions
that are commonly used

00:08:34.913 --> 00:08:37.252
we tend to think that the benefits

00:08:37.252 --> 00:08:40.654
likely outweigh that negative.

00:08:40.654 --> 00:08:45.270
And really focusing on
infancy and early childhood

00:08:45.270 --> 00:08:48.240
is a great time period
to try to understand how

00:08:48.240 --> 00:08:52.055
these conditions develop
and to help with improving

00:08:52.055 --> 00:08:56.400
accurate earlier detection,
identifying the time periods

00:08:56.400 --> 00:08:58.710
that are most important for identification

00:08:58.710 --> 00:09:02.700
and maybe early intervention
and what areas of functioning

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:04.940
are the most relevant in
this developmental period

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:07.874
that might help us
identify autism earlier.

00:09:07.874 --> 00:09:11.840
So the next question is how do we do it.

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:14.730
And what I'm gonna tell
you about is one particular

00:09:14.730 --> 00:09:18.020
study design that gets
used to try to identify

00:09:18.020 --> 00:09:21.593
early signs of autism and
this is focused on siblings.

00:09:21.593 --> 00:09:25.350
So it's called an infant
sibling study design

00:09:25.350 --> 00:09:28.670
and what we do is we study families.

00:09:28.670 --> 00:09:30.990
So we have the parents here
and then they have a child

00:09:30.990 --> 00:09:33.880
with autism and then the family has a baby

00:09:33.880 --> 00:09:36.320
and this baby is considered
to at elevated risk

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:39.935
for autism based on
family history genetics.

00:09:39.935 --> 00:09:43.410
So we know the recurrent
rate of autism in younger

00:09:43.410 --> 00:09:45.870
siblings of children with
autism is significantly higher

00:09:45.870 --> 00:09:48.580
than the rate in the general population.

00:09:48.580 --> 00:09:51.812
And then we have our
comparison group of babies

00:09:51.812 --> 00:09:54.894
who have only typically
developing older siblings,

00:09:54.894 --> 00:09:57.194
no family history of
autism spectrum disorder.

00:09:58.110 --> 00:10:02.950
And then we have them come
into the lab for assessments

00:10:02.950 --> 00:10:05.192
at regular intervals in the
first several years of life

00:10:05.192 --> 00:10:10.109
so they would come in at
six, nine, 12, 15, 18,

00:10:10.109 --> 00:10:13.110
24 and 36 months of life
and we'll do a whole

00:10:13.110 --> 00:10:15.110
range of assessments with them.

00:10:15.110 --> 00:10:18.780
Developmental assessments,
we'll do some eye tracking

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:21.260
assessments to see kind
of what they'll focus on

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:24.520
and are interested in, parents
will fill out a variety

00:10:24.520 --> 00:10:27.740
of questionnaires,
starting at 18 months we'll

00:10:27.740 --> 00:10:31.446
do an ADOS which is the Autism
Diagnostic Observation skill

00:10:31.446 --> 00:10:34.693
and then when they turn three
we'll determine which babies

00:10:34.693 --> 00:10:38.173
went on and developed autism by age three.

00:10:39.769 --> 00:10:41.630
And which babies ended being
typically developing and then

00:10:41.630 --> 00:10:44.280
we could go back and look at
all of the data and see where

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:46.129
the difference is between
those groups of children begin

00:10:46.129 --> 00:10:48.712
to emerge and in what
areas of functioning.

00:10:48.712 --> 00:10:53.710
So I'll just say that if a
child meets criteria before

00:10:53.710 --> 00:10:56.726
age we will certainly make
the diagnosis and provide

00:10:56.726 --> 00:10:59.750
referrals and recommendations
but kind of the final

00:10:59.750 --> 00:11:02.632
determination for the
studies at age three.

00:11:02.632 --> 00:11:07.570
Interesting I think excitingly
Sally Ozonoff has gotten

00:11:07.570 --> 00:11:09.952
a follow up grant to study
cohorts of these babies

00:11:09.952 --> 00:11:14.952
into school age period, so
now they're between seven

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:18.068
and fourteen and we're seeing them back

00:11:18.068 --> 00:11:21.270
to see how they're functioning
later in development.

00:11:21.270 --> 00:11:23.770
Whether they develop autism
or not so all of them.

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:27.870
So in terms of what we're
learning from siblings

00:11:27.870 --> 00:11:30.640
in the infancy period,
we're learning about

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:34.120
the recurrence risk for autism,
we're learning about how

00:11:34.120 --> 00:11:37.549
symptoms emerge on onset,
what are the early markers.

00:11:37.549 --> 00:11:40.050
I'm not gonna talk
about biological markers

00:11:40.050 --> 00:11:42.890
but some studies using
this study design do study,

00:11:42.890 --> 00:11:47.580
they do brain scans or
EEG I'll talk a bit about

00:11:47.580 --> 00:11:49.410
some of the behavioral markers.

00:11:49.410 --> 00:11:51.810
And then we can learn more about target

00:11:51.810 --> 00:11:54.233
for prevention and intervention programs.

00:11:55.820 --> 00:11:59.810
So in terms of recurrence
risk, previously it was thought

00:11:59.810 --> 00:12:03.850
that about three to 10% of
younger siblings of children

00:12:03.850 --> 00:12:06.450
with autism would
develop autism themselves

00:12:06.450 --> 00:12:09.440
which is significantly
higher than the population

00:12:09.440 --> 00:12:12.252
prevalence but through these
infant sibling study design

00:12:12.252 --> 00:12:15.520
there's a consortium
across the globe really

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:19.010
with multiple investigators
involved called the baby

00:12:19.010 --> 00:12:21.780
siblings research consortium
and they've pooled their data.

00:12:21.780 --> 00:12:24.071
They all sort of follow
this study design to answer

00:12:24.071 --> 00:12:27.410
this question of what's
the updated recurrence rate

00:12:27.410 --> 00:12:30.253
in these samples that we get
from these types of studies.

00:12:30.253 --> 00:12:33.580
And it's much closer to
20% at least in these

00:12:33.580 --> 00:12:36.133
infant sibling samples that we've studied

00:12:36.133 --> 00:12:38.670
which is significantly
higher than we thought

00:12:38.670 --> 00:12:41.240
and certainly significantly
higher than the general

00:12:41.240 --> 00:12:43.200
population prevalence
of about one and a half

00:12:43.200 --> 00:12:45.053
percent which was referenced earlier.

00:12:46.930 --> 00:12:49.300
So that has some implications
I think about kind

00:12:49.300 --> 00:12:52.900
of what families are thinking
about and I think it's helpful

00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:57.710
to know just so you can monitor
and watch for early signs.

00:12:57.710 --> 00:13:01.600
In terms of those early
signs and in terms of early

00:13:01.600 --> 00:13:03.440
behavioral markers that
we might be looking for

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:06.520
especially thinking about
the symptoms of autism,

00:13:06.520 --> 00:13:08.970
social communication
challenges and then also

00:13:08.970 --> 00:13:11.130
thinking about infancy or early childhood.

00:13:11.130 --> 00:13:14.040
We're really looking for
things like differences

00:13:14.040 --> 00:13:16.693
in eye gaze, differences in
frequency of vocalization,

00:13:16.693 --> 00:13:20.135
