low flat trajectories

00:14:22.574 --> 00:14:23.443
in the group who went
on to develop autism.

00:14:24.649 --> 00:14:26.460
And the differences really
begin to emerge between

00:14:27.531 --> 00:14:30.410
12 and 18 months of age or we
see these changes happening.

00:14:30.410 --> 00:14:33.130
What I think is really
interesting and especially

00:14:33.130 --> 00:14:36.550
for clinicians is that when
we ask clinicians to rate

00:14:36.550 --> 00:14:39.234
very similar behaviors after
they have assessed the child

00:14:39.234 --> 00:14:42.880
and these are blind examiners
they don't know anything

00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:45.510
about the family history, they
don't know whether they're

00:14:45.510 --> 00:14:48.240
at risk for autism or
not at risk for autism.

00:14:48.240 --> 00:14:50.600
You see a really similar
pattern in these declining

00:14:50.600 --> 00:14:53.650
trajectories of the examiner
or expert kind of clinician

00:14:53.650 --> 00:14:56.480
ratings with the
differences really becoming

00:14:56.480 --> 00:14:58.440
most different between 12 and 18 months.

00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:01.220
So I think we can kind of get
at the same thing that this

00:15:01.220 --> 00:15:04.213
pain staking really takes a
long time to do this coding

00:15:04.213 --> 00:15:06.935
we can get at the same thing
from the clinician ratings.

00:15:06.935 --> 00:15:11.935
In terms of another social
behavior that we've noticed

00:15:12.613 --> 00:15:15.312
is different in infants who
are going on to develop autism

00:15:15.312 --> 00:15:20.312
it's response to names, so
we know that infants use

00:15:20.732 --> 00:15:22.630
their names as social cues
which helps them to orient

00:15:22.630 --> 00:15:25.460
to salient aspects of
their environment including

00:15:25.460 --> 00:15:30.393
social partners and what
has been shown in the past

00:15:30.393 --> 00:15:33.840
is that there has been a
diminishment in the response

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:36.730
to name by about 12 months of age.

00:15:36.730 --> 00:15:39.730
And this was found in
babies who developed autism

00:15:39.730 --> 00:15:42.730
but this was found using retrospective

00:15:42.730 --> 00:15:47.730
chart review or videos basically
or paper pencil measures

00:15:47.773 --> 00:15:51.093
that parents fill out and
so we really wanted to look

00:15:51.093 --> 00:15:54.513
at this from our
prospectively collected data.

00:15:54.513 --> 00:15:57.911
And kind of overtime so the
developmental progression

00:15:57.911 --> 00:16:02.250
of responding to name and what we found.

00:16:02.250 --> 00:16:06.500
So we used a measure from
it's the AOSI, it's a task

00:16:06.500 --> 00:16:10.400
that this is an item from
that task where examiner

00:16:11.411 --> 00:16:13.072
calls the baby's name up to two times

00:16:13.072 --> 00:16:15.627
and there are two trials like that.

00:16:15.627 --> 00:16:17.860
So up to four total times at
different intervals during

00:16:17.860 --> 00:16:20.710
the assessment and we
were pretty stringent

00:16:20.710 --> 00:16:24.120
in our definition of a
failure so to fail we said

00:16:24.120 --> 00:16:26.673
that they had to not respond
to any of the four trials.

00:16:26.673 --> 00:16:30.450
And what we found was that the
group who went on to develop

00:16:30.450 --> 00:16:33.900
autism was more likely to
fail by nine months of age

00:16:33.900 --> 00:16:36.320
and persisting through 24 months of age.

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:39.190
So this appears to be
distinguishing that group

00:16:39.190 --> 00:16:41.183
as early as nine months of age.

00:16:43.360 --> 00:16:46.410
So ultimately I think this
work focused on infants

00:16:46.410 --> 00:16:49.434
at risk for autism has
kind of resulted in a lot

00:16:49.434 --> 00:16:53.510
important information
for clinical practice

00:16:53.510 --> 00:16:56.071
and I think that it has made
its way into clinical practice.

00:16:56.071 --> 00:17:00.700
Related to red flags and
early screenings for autism

00:17:00.700 --> 00:17:02.820
in the first couple of years of life.

00:17:02.820 --> 00:17:05.410
So I think families know
a lot more because they've

00:17:05.410 --> 00:17:08.090
heard a lot more about these early signs,

00:17:08.090 --> 00:17:11.160
they're watching for it, the
American Academy of Pediatrics

00:17:11.160 --> 00:17:14.831
have implemented kind of
regular or universal screening

00:17:14.831 --> 00:17:17.530
at specific intervals with recommended

00:17:17.530 --> 00:17:21.350
measures early in life
so I think it has some

00:17:21.350 --> 00:17:24.815
significant clinical impact thus far.

00:17:24.815 --> 00:17:29.640
Now I mentioned earlier
that about just under 20%

00:17:29.640 --> 00:17:32.540
of these infant siblings
go on to develop autism

00:17:32.540 --> 00:17:35.670
by age three but so if you do your math

00:17:35.670 --> 00:17:37.210
it means most of them don't, right.

00:17:37.210 --> 00:17:39.480
So there's a question about
what about all of these

00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:43.113
other children who were at
risk but did not develop autism

00:17:43.113 --> 00:17:47.440
and so we've been interested
in this concept of the broader

00:17:47.440 --> 00:17:50.600
autism phenotype so
sort of non diagnostic,

00:17:50.600 --> 00:17:53.771
sub clinical, more like
traits or characteristics

00:17:53.771 --> 00:17:57.110
that are kind of inline with
autism spectrum disorder.

00:17:57.110 --> 00:17:59.610
So sub threshold social
communication challenges

00:17:59.610 --> 00:18:02.680
for example but are not
at the clinical level.

00:18:02.680 --> 00:18:05.595
And we see this sometimes in
family members of individuals

00:18:05.595 --> 00:18:08.655
with autism and we were
interested in trying to understand

00:18:08.655 --> 00:18:13.653
how early can we identify
those sub clinical differences.

00:18:13.653 --> 00:18:18.210
So what we did was we
characterized our sample of these

00:18:18.210 --> 00:18:23.140
babies when they were three,
whether they were typically

00:18:23.140 --> 00:18:25.650
developing or non
typically developing based

00:18:25.650 --> 00:18:29.060
on their MULLEN standardized
developing scores

00:18:29.060 --> 00:18:33.350
and or ADOS scores being
within several points

00:18:33.350 --> 00:18:37.280
of the autism cut off and
then looked backward to see

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:39.940
where did that group of
children start to differ

00:18:39.940 --> 00:18:42.170
from the children who
were typically developing.

00:18:42.170 --> 00:18:45.180
And the answer was around 12 months of age

00:18:45.180 --> 00:18:48.240
that we say differences, so
again we can see differences

00:18:48.240 --> 00:18:52.330
in these children who are
experiencing some threshold

00:18:52.330 --> 00:18:54.928
challenges even earlier
than we kind of expected.

00:18:54.928 --> 00:18:59.928
So now the question is
that's up to age three

00:18:59.950 --> 00:19:02.730
and there's been a lot of
work across all of these

00:19:02.730 --> 00:19:05.760
baby sibling consortium
sights to study these infant

00:19:06.751 --> 00:19:10.480
siblings up to age three
but then it sort of stopped.

00:19:10.480 --> 00:19:13.195
And of course we all know that
children continue to develop

00:19:13.195 --> 00:19:16.330
and that's one of the reasons
that we've been interested

00:19:16.330 --> 00:19:19.160
and Sally Ozonoff has been
interested in understanding

00:19:19.160 --> 00:19:20.970
some of the longer term outcomes of these

00:19:20.970 --> 00:19:23.893
siblings beyond the preschool period.

00:19:23.893 --> 00:19:28.833
And again 80% of younger
siblings don't develop autism

00:19:28.833 --> 00:19:32.820
but are there risks for
other things that come along

00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:35.348
later in life, that's a
question that's worth answering

00:19:35.348 --> 00:19:39.500
and the answer is generally yeah.

00:19:39.500 --> 00:19:42.893
So about 35% we found of
children develop some other

00:19:42.893 --> 00:19:47.660
non ASD concern by school age
that doesn't mean diagnosable

00:19:47.660 --> 00:19:50.308
but some level of concern
across a variety of different

00:19:50.308 --> 00:19:52.593
measures so I'll give you some examples.

00:19:52.593 --> 00:19:57.593
This is sort of a pilot
project that was looking

00:19:58.470 --> 00:20:01.330
at one cohort of these baby
siblings when they were

00:20:01.330 --> 00:20:03.870
six to eight years of age,
so they had grown up into

00:20:03.870 --> 00:20:07.820
that early school age period
and what we found here

00:20:07.820 --> 00:20:10.730
is kind of when we looked
at it different ways we kind

00:20:10.730 --> 00:20:13.180
of found the same thing
whether we were looking

00:20:13.180 --> 00:20:16.492
at clinical concerns as
expressed by a clinician

00:20:16.492 --> 00:20:21.492
who assessed the child or
scores above clinical cutoff

00:20:21.873 --> 00:20:25.530
on measures of psycho pathology
symptoms like depression,

00:20:25.530 --> 00:20:30.530
anxiety or autism related
symptoms or language scores

00:20:31.220 --> 00:20:32.810
on standardized language testing.

00:20:32.810 --> 00:20:37.090
We see a higher proportion
of the group who has a family

00:20:37.090 --> 00:20:39.780
history of autism falling
into that impaired

00:20:39.780 --> 00:20:42.880
or concerning range and
these are the children

00:20:43.834 --> 00:20:45.680
who do not have autism themselves.

00:20:45.680 --> 00:20:48.896
So I like I said anywhere
from 25 to 40% of these

00:20:48.896 --> 00:20:51.950
siblings were falling into these sort

00:20:51.950 --> 00:20:54.254
of elevated or clinical concern ranges.

00:20:54.254 --> 00:20:58.130
Now one of the things that was
coming up in that age range

00:20:58.130 --> 00:21:01.516
a lot for us was concerns
about ADHD and so we

00:21:01.516 --> 00:21:05.115
did another sort of smaller
pilot where we looked

00:21:05.115 --> 00:21:07.470
at eight to 11 years of age
and really tried to do a better

00:21:07.470 --> 00:21:12.353
job of characterizing ADHD
and I think there is some

00:21:12.353 --> 00:21:16.893
caveat I would mention
here, you could see a pretty

00:21:16.893 --> 00:21:20.597
high rate of ADHD in our low risk group.

00:21:20.597 --> 00:21:23.813
So it's certainly
possible that the families

00:21:23.813 --> 00:21:25.480
that are most concerned
are the ones who came back

00:21:26.454 --> 00:21:28.740
really easily but there
is a difference in terms

00:21:30.076 --> 00:21:31.970
of the group that had a
family history of autism had

00:21:31.970 --> 00:21:35.515
significantly higher rates of
ADHD than our low risk group.

00:21:35.515 --> 00:21:40.515
So that kind of piqued our
interest and led to the current

00:21:41.351 --> 00:21:45.036
follow up that we're
doing a little bit older,

00:21:45.036 --> 00:21:49.547
12 to 15 years of age
for most of the children,

00:21:49.547 --> 00:21:52.960
some of them may come in
a little earlier than that

00:21:52.960 --> 00:21:57.011
maybe eight to 15 in the end
across three different cohorts

00:21:57.011 --> 00:22:00.350
that had been recruited in
the last 15 years or so.

00:22:00.350 --> 00:22:04.350
And we're doing more comprehensive
assessments of symptoms

00:22:04.350 --> 00:22:08.616
of psychopathology like
ADHD, anxiety, mood concerns,

00:22:08.616 --> 00:22:12.470
so we're doing a full diagnostic
workup on those things.

00:22:12.470 --> 00:22:16.110
We're also assessing academic
skills, pragmatic language

00:22:16.110 --> 00:22:19.593
abilities which we know are
challenging for children

00:22:19.593 --> 00:22:21.660
with autism but also there's
suggestion that it may

00:22:22.635 --> 00:22:24.490
be an area that's a little
bit challenging for siblings

00:22:25.711 --> 00:22:28.091
who don't have autism, we're
kind of doing a deep dive

00:22:28.091 --> 00:22:29.880
into their attention skill,
their activity level,

00:22:29.880 --> 00:22:33.274
their ability to control
their inhibitions.

00:22:33.274 --> 00:22:38.200
Or kind of inhibit the responses
and then lastly I think

00:22:38.200 --> 00:22:41.050
really importantly their
peer relationships and social

00:22:41.050 --> 00:22:43.740
functioning so we're having
teachers fill out ratings

00:22:43.740 --> 00:22:47.250
about how well the child
is liked and how what their

00:22:47.250 --> 00:22:49.000
social skills are like, how many friends

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:51.350
they have those kinds of things.

00:22:51.350 --> 00:22:53.940
And one of the reasons we're
really interested in doing

00:22:53.940 --> 00:22:55.960
this is because we really want
to understand how siblings

00:22:55.960 --> 00:22:58.890
are functioning later in
development but we also see

00:22:58.890 --> 00:23:02.870
these higher rates of other
kind of concerns outcomes

00:23:02.870 --> 00:23:05.680
in this population and so
our thinking is that we might

00:23:05.680 --> 00:23:10.210
be able by following them up
to use the data that we've

00:23:10.210 --> 00:23:13.410
been collecting for the last
15 year for their whole lives

00:23:13.410 --> 00:23:16.390
really to predict other
non autism outcomes.

00:23:16.390 --> 00:23:19.350
Like what might be early
markers of ADHD, what might

00:23:19.350 --> 00:23:21.731
be early markers of
anxiety in these siblings.

00:23:21.731 --> 00:23:26.553
So I don't know if we'll
get to adulthood through

00:23:26.553 --> 00:23:28.893
following these same
cohorts but there have been

00:23:28.893 --> 00:23:33.893
certainly studies of
adult siblings of children

00:23:34.290 --> 00:23:37.350
with autism, this is not work
that we've done ourselves.

00:23:37.350 --> 00:23:41.160
But there was a study a
few years back by Holland

00:23:41.160 --> 00:23:44.096
where they looked at 87
adult siblings of children

00:23:44.096 --> 00:23:47.236
with autism, the average
age was just under 40.

00:23:47.236 --> 00:23:51.155
And they had a group within
this group of siblings

00:23:51.155 --> 00:23:55.300
a sub group that had previously
been evaluated at a prior

00:23:55.300 --> 00:23:59.920
time point and identified
as either having that kind

00:23:59.920 --> 00:24:02.991
of broader autism phenotype
traits and sub threshold

00:24:02.991 --> 00:24:07.811
symptoms or traits
characteristics were unaffected

00:24:07.811 --> 00:24:12.000
or typically developing and
when they followed them up

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:14.460
at this adult time point
what they found was that

00:24:14.460 --> 00:24:17.490
the previously determined
or defined unaffected group

00:24:17.490 --> 00:24:22.194
had average intellectual
functioning, basic academic skills.

00:24:22.194 --> 00:24:25.332
They were functioning really well in jobs,

00:24:25.332 --> 00:24:28.180
in their independence and
their social relationships,

00:24:28.180 --> 00:24:31.592
so they were just functioning
average or above average.

00:24:31.592 --> 00:24:34.870
The group that had been
previously identified as having

00:24:34.870 --> 00:24:37.960
some of these sub threshold
characteristics had some

00:24:37.960 --> 00:24:40.740
challenges with employment,
they had lower social

00:24:40.740 --> 00:24:45.180
relationship levels and
they had elevated ASD traits

00:24:45.180 --> 00:24:47.900
as would be expected as
well as elevated rates

00:24:47.900 --> 00:24:50.270
of other mental health symptoms.

00:24:50.270 --> 00:24:53.553
So this is I hope you can
see it relatively well,

00:24:53.553 --> 00:24:57.175
but the group in pink is
that group that had the

00:24:57.175 --> 00:25:00.230
sub threshold autism
traits in an earlier age

00:25:00.230 --> 00:25:04.420
and what you can see here
is that they're elevated

00:25:04.420 --> 00:25:08.030
across several different
aspects of functioning

00:25:08.030 --> 00:25:12.790
so OCD symptoms, so
episodic depression symptoms

00:25:13.934 --> 00:25:18.096
was the same but chronic
depression symptoms was different,

00:25:18.096 --> 00:25:23.096
higher levels of anxiety and
higher rates of being above

00:25:23.100 --> 00:25:26.734
a clinical threshold for
ADHD and these were symptoms

00:25:26.734 --> 00:25:29.730
here that actually had
the required treatment.

00:25:29.730 --> 00:25:31.909
So this was significantly
elevated symptoms,

00:25:31.909 --> 00:25:34.913
so there do seem to be some
concerns that persist across

00:25:34.913 --> 00:25:38.870
the lifespan for a subset
of siblings of children

00:25:38.870 --> 00:25:41.563
with autism who don't
have autism themselves.

00:25:42.710 --> 00:25:45.652
So just to summarize here
I would say that we've made

00:25:45.652 --> 00:25:48.610
a lot of progress by studying
siblings in the early

00:25:48.610 --> 00:25:52.450
detection of autism spectrum disorder.

00:25:52.450 --> 00:25:54.740
That I do think have clear
implications for clinical

00:25:54.740 --> 00:25:57.060
practice especially for
those of us who are working

00:25:57.060 --> 00:25:59.950
in the early intervention,
early identification role.

00:25:59.950 --> 00:26:04.610
The birth to three world
and I think as a result

00:26:04.610 --> 00:26:07.250
of studying these baby
siblings we're realizing that

00:26:07.250 --> 00:26:09.210
there's a really big
gap here that we really

00:26:09.210 --> 00:26:10.840
don't know about longer term outcomes.

00:26:10.840 --> 00:26:12.890
We've sort of just kind
of cut them off at three

00:26:12.890 --> 00:26:15.792
and then moved on but we have
this opportunity to really

00:26:15.792 --> 00:26:20.792
understand the full developmental
life course by continuing

00:26:21.013 --> 00:26:25.250
to follow up these siblings
who have truly been enrolled

00:26:25.250 --> 00:26:29.430
in these studies since the
beginning of their lives

00:26:29.430 --> 00:26:32.230
which is pretty amazing, and
this could help us really

00:26:32.230 --> 00:26:35.674
understand early predictors
of other outcomes

00:26:35.674 --> 00:26:38.730
later in life like ADHD for example.

00:26:38.730 --> 00:26:41.960
I think the other thing we
really need to do more of is try

00:26:41.960 --> 00:26:44.800
to understand resilience
and protective factors

00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:47.770
and I think these studies,
these samples really provide

00:26:47.770 --> 00:26:49.680
an opportunity for that as well.

00:26:49.680 --> 00:26:52.010
And so I think we'll
probably start to see more

00:26:52.010 --> 00:26:53.763
of that over the next few years.

00:26:55.490 --> 00:26:59.880
I just wanna put a plug out
because we're not too far

00:26:59.880 --> 00:27:03.348
from the MIND Institute for
a study that I'm currently

00:27:03.348 --> 00:27:06.210
doing and we have lots
of families who enroll

00:27:06.210 --> 00:27:09.935
from the Bay Area but if you
have any clients or patients

00:27:09.935 --> 00:27:13.180
or know any families
that might be interested

00:27:13.180 --> 00:27:15.420
in this type of work where
we do kind of regular

00:27:15.420 --> 00:27:18.960
close monitoring of
the babies development.

00:27:18.960 --> 00:27:22.416
We're recruiting babies and
we're doing an infant sibling

00:27:22.416 --> 00:27:27.110
study that's kind of combined
across autism risk and ADHD.

00:27:27.110 --> 00:27:29.660
So we're also studying babies
at risk for ADHD to see

00:27:29.660 --> 00:27:32.680
if we can apply the same
methods that have been so useful

00:27:32.680 --> 00:27:35.170
in autism that have been
used to identify some early

00:27:35.170 --> 00:27:38.480
markers of ADHD as well,
so there's information

00:27:38.480 --> 00:27:41.495
there if you're interested,
so I'll just like to thank

00:27:41.495 --> 00:27:45.670
the early risk study lab
which is my lab and the

00:27:45.670 --> 00:27:48.780
infant sibling study which
is Sally Ozonoff's study.

00:27:48.780 --> 00:27:50.810
A lot of the data that I
shared with you today is from

00:27:50.810 --> 00:27:53.700
her research that I have
just been fortunate to be

00:27:53.700 --> 00:27:55.730
a part of for the last several years.

00:27:55.730 --> 00:27:57.937
As well as funding sources
and my contact information

00:27:57.937 --> 00:28:00.929
is available here if you
have any follow up questions.

00:28:00.929 --> 00:28:03.488
And I think there will
be a few minutes after

00:28:03.488 --> 00:28:08.153
the Kagel's talk now, thank you very much.

00:28:08.153 --> 00:28:11.153
